description: From Middle English caraway, carewey, carwey, from Medieval Latin carui, from Arabic كَرَاوِيَا‎ (karāwiyā), via Aramaic from Ancient Greek καρώ (karṓ), κάρον (káron, “caraway”).

entries.meaning: A biennial plant, Carum carvi, native to Europe and Asia, mainly grown for its seed to be used as a culinary spice.
The seed-like fruit of the caraway plant.
A cake or sweetmeat containing caraway seeds.
examples: I'll eat her marchpane and her caraways
